d a curtain. You came with dusk still in your prism-lamp and the river’s code in your knuckles, and the copper ward-tile at your chest feels heavier, as if the Shard’s hum has found it and is asking whether you keep oaths as tightly as you keep your blade.\",\n      \"objectives\": [\"Enter the Silent Archive with Sava’s scribe pass.\", \"Locate the palimpsest listing Night Orchard founders and collar cavity schedules.\", \"Make an accurate copy without removing the original.\", \"Avoid detection by compromised scribes and House Kelvar agents.\"],\n      \"dialogue\": [\n        {\"speaker\": \"Sava Inkweft\", \"lines\": \"Records are oaths that learned to sit still, Jaryn, and the Archive is where we set out bread and water for them until they speak clearly. If we burn them, we burn our own road home, because no one remembers the way without a lantern held up to the old markers. This palimpsest is not a sword to cut throats with; it’s a mirror to make proud faces blink and notice the blood already on their collars and the threads tying their hands. Copy it clean, fold it into your belt, and bring it to a hall where words are weighed and not merely shouted, because shouting is a wind that forgets its own direction. I ask you because you have carried both secrets and soup, and I have seen you choose to feed first and boast later, and that is the temper a page like this demands. House Kelvar wants it salted down to a silence; the Order wants it sealed and sung over until the ink forgets it was ever wet; the Orchard wants it named but not shouted. I want it remembered in daylight by people who keep ledgers of grain and grief, not just debt, and I want it done without tearing the Archive’s skin.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Jaryn Chainwake\", \"lines\": \"I won’t steal from the city’s memory, Sava, not for coin, not for favor, not for any hand that thinks a ledger is a leash. I will copy and leave the bones where they lie, and I will keep my breath smooth so the paper does not feel my haste and twitch into error. If someone tries to take a bite out of the page while it’s in my hands, they’ll crack their teeth on glass and spit their own blood into the lime dust, because I carry more than ink when the river asks for backbone. The last time I hid a thing under the Chainbridge it grew teeth and keys, and the rumor of it still nips my sleep; I have no taste to repeat a mistake that taught me how deep the Shard’s collars can swallow a promise. I’ll use my prism-lamp shuttered to a scribe’s rhythm, I’ll count heartbeats between the seep’s whispers, and I’ll keep the copper ward-tile warm with skin so it remembers what we swore. If we walk out with nothing but a faithful twin and our names unblotted, that will be a better victory than any purse of beads.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Iven Shadequinch\", \"lines\": \"You have a gardener’s hands when you choose, riverborn, and gardeners know how to cut without killing the tree that shades the street. Trim the truth, don’t hack it, because hacked wood scars ugly and draws beetles, and beetles call birds with bigger hungers. The Gardener will not weep if old roots are named, but he will prune any branch that breaks the canopy to boast, because sunlight is a ration we share and reputation is a crop we tend together. Do your work and step lightly out, and if you must speak, speak in rooms that have windows on the river so the current can carry away what heat gathers. There are eyes in the ink and ears in the clay tubes, and some of them are ours and some of them are rented, and you will not always know the difference by the shine. Take care with ladders, especially the kind that hide in collars, for those rungs lead to councils where people forget gravity and fall upward into arrogance.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Rook Salter\", \"lines\": \"Funny to see you down here, Chainwake; the last time I saw your back it was braced under a chain that wanted you drowned, and I wondered which ledger had 