 stays in step with the lamp’s steady glow until street noises fold over you like river foam.\"},\n        {\"id\": \"C3\", \"title\": \"Knot-Decoy and Candle-Ward Diversion\", \"text\": \"You prepare a decoy not to replace the original but to give hungry eyes something loud to chew: a bead-knot cord strung in the same count as the palimpsest’s secret schedule, hung casually on a peg as if forgotten. Sava lights three extra candles down a side corridor and places a ward-tile that sings just enough to draw the curious, inventing a small crisis about ‘heat-levy wax’ that will keep petty minds busy. You copy the real under-script in the brief quiet, your reed moving in small tides while the Archive’s air turns warm with false importance elsewhere, and you time your strokes to the ward’s soft keen. When footsteps near, you perform a small, honest act of clumsiness and drop a stack of empty clay tubes; the clatter collapses neatly into your diversion and encourages people to scold you for what you did not break. Rook Salter sidles up, smells the bait cord, and decides he has found the prize he came for, and in that decision he stops looking at your hands and your lamp entirely.\", \"outcome\": \"Your copy slides into your belt-sheath without a fingerprint while the decoy cord slips out of the Archive under a lesser man’s cloak, and for two days the wrong rumor runs hot in Mirrorclose: that the secret was never ink at all but knots you could cut. House Kelvar spends coin on cutters skilled in hair-bead arithmetic and wastes a week unraveling a thread that leads nowhere, which costs you nothing and costs them patience. The Order declares that candle-wards must be signed out by number henceforth, which inconveniences the Archive but pleases chair-sitters who like new forms; Sava sighs and shrugs because the price of truth is sometimes a small annoyance. The Night Orchard notes that you threw a bright scrap to the gulls and kept the fish for supper, and their respect tilts t